<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-negative-enlargements" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Negative Enlargements</title>

    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.1 Similarity and Enlargement
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Construct the image of an object under an enlargement given the centre and the linear scale factor.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define negative scale factor enlargement as a transformation where the image is formed on the opposite side of the centre and is inverted. Distinguish between positive and negative scale factor enlargements.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Construct the image of a shape under enlargement with a negative scale factor by drawing lines through the centre, measuring distances, and plotting image points on the opposite side. Calculate image coordinates using the formula <m>(x', y') = (kx, ky)</m> for origin-centred enlargements.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply negative scale factor enlargement to determine image coordinates, find unknown distances, and solve problems involving circles, triangles, and real-world contexts such as photographs and maps.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                  <p>
                     <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/similarity-and-enlargement/negative-enlargements.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                     <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/similarity-and-enlargement/step-by-step-guide_negative-enlargements.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                  </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>What Happens When the Scale Factor Is Negative?</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Work in pairs
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate among pairs, asking probing questions: <q>Where is <m>A'</m> relative to <m>O</m>?</q>, <q>Is <m>A'</m> on the same side as <m>A</m>?</q> Expected answers: <m>A'=(-2,-1)</m>, <m>B'=(-4,-1)</m>, <m>C'=(-3,-3)</m>. Image is on the OPPOSITE side of the centre, INVERTED. Same size. Scale factor <m>= -1</m>. The triangles are congruent but rotated <m>180^\circ</m> about <m>O</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Draw axes with origin <m>O</m>. Plot <m>A(2,1)</m>, <m>B(4,1)</m>, <m>C(3,3)</m>. Form <m>\triangle ABC</m>. For each vertex, draw a line THROUGH the origin to the OTHER SIDE. Mark a point at the SAME distance from <m>O</m> on the opposite side as <m>A'</m>, <m>B'</m>, <m>C'</m>. Form <m>\triangle A'B'C'</m>. Write the coordinates. Compare with the original. Note the orientation.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Main Activity -->
    <activity xml:id="activity-negative-enlargements">
        <introduction>
             <p><alert>Work in pairs</alert></p>
        </introduction>

        <task xml:id="task-draw-axes">
            <statement>
                <p>Draw and label the <m>x</m>-axis and <m>y</m>-axis on the graph paper.</p>
                <image source="graph-paper.png">
                    <shortdescription>A graph paper showing perpendicular x and y axes intersecting at the origin (0,0).</shortdescription>
                </image>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-mark-origin">
            <statement>
                <p>Mark the origin at <m>(0,0)</m> and label it <m>\textbf{O}</m>. This point will be the centre of enlargement.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-plot-points">
            <statement>
                <p>Plot the points <m>A(2,3)</m>, <m>B(1,1)</m>, and <m>C(4,1)</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-form-triangle">
            <statement>
                <p>Join <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> using straight lines to form triangle <m>ABC</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-extend-lines">
            <statement>
                <p>Draw straight lines from the centre <m>O</m> through each vertex <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>. Extend each line beyond the centre to the opposite side.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-measure-distances">
            <statement>
                <p>Measure the distances <m>OA</m>, <m>OB</m>, and <m>OC</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-mark-image-points">
            <statement>
                <p>Using a scale factor of <m>-2</m>, mark new points on the opposite side of the centre along the same straight lines such that:</p>
                <p><m>OA' = -2 \times OA</m>, <m>OB' = -2 \times OB</m>, <m>OC' = -2 \times OC</m></p>
                <p>Label the new points <m>A'</m>, <m>B'</m>, and <m>C'</m>.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-form-image-triangle">
            <statement>
                <p>Join <m>A'</m>, <m>B'</m>, and <m>C'</m> to form triangle <m>A'B'C'</m>, the image of triangle <m>ABC</m> under a negative enlargement.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-compare-triangles">
            <statement>
                <p>Compare triangle <m>ABC</m> and triangle <m>A'B'C'</m>. What do you observe about:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Their shapes?</li>
                    <li>Their sizes?</li>
                    <li>Their orientation?</li>
                    <li>Their positions relative to the centre?</li>
                </ul>
            </statement>
        </task>

        <task xml:id="task-discuss">
            <statement>
                <p>Discuss your findings with the rest of the class.</p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </activity>
    <figure>
        <caption>Negative Enlargement of a Rectangle</caption>
        <interactive xml:id="negative-enlargement" platform="jsxgraph" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/negative_enlargement.js" width="100%">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-negative-enlargement" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3" />
            <instructions xml:id="negative-enlargement-instructions">
                <p>Use the scale factor slider at the top left to vary the scale factor <m>k</m> between <m>-3</m> and <m>3</m>. Observe how a negative scale factor inverts the rectangle across the center of enlargement <m>O</m>, appearing on the opposite side of the dashed construction lines. You can drag the center <m>O</m>, or the diagonal vertices <m>A</m> and <m>C</m> to resize the original rectangle.</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the definition and properties of negative enlargement.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Negative Scale Factor:</alert> The image is on the OPPOSITE side of the centre and is INVERTED.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Coordinate Rule:</alert> For an enlargement centred at the origin with scale factor <m>k</m>, the image of <m>(x,y)</m> is <m>(kx, ky)</m>. When <m>k</m> is negative, the signs change.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Special Cases:</alert> <m>k = -1</m>: same size, inverted. <m>|k| \gt 1</m> (e.g. <m>k = -2</m>): larger AND inverted. <m>0 \gt k \gt -1</m> (e.g. <m>k = -\frac{1}{2}</m>): smaller AND inverted.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Key Insight:</alert> The <q>negative</q> controls DIRECTION (opposite side), the absolute value controls SIZE.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Comparison Table: Positive vs Negative Scale Factor</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Property</cell>
                    <cell>Positive SF</cell>
                    <cell>Negative SF</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Position</cell>
                    <cell>Same side of centre</cell>
                    <cell>Opposite side of centre</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Orientation</cell>
                    <cell>Same as object</cell>
                    <cell>Inverted (rotated <m>180^\circ</m>)</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>|k| \gt 1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Larger</cell>
                    <cell>Larger AND inverted</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>|k| \lt 1</m></cell>
                    <cell>Smaller</cell>
                    <cell>Smaller AND inverted</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p><alert>A negative enlargement</alert> is a transformation where the image is produced on the <m>\textbf{opposite side}</m> of the center of enlargement from the original shape. The scale factor is negative, indicating a change in orientation.</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>When the scale factor is negative (e.g., <m>-2</m>), both the size and position of the shape change. The image is enlarged (or reduced) and rotated <m>180^\circ</m> about the center of enlargement. The magnitude of the scale factor determines how much larger or smaller the image becomes.</p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>For a negative enlargement with scale factor <m>k</m> 
                        (where <m>k &lt; 0</m>):
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>The distance from center to image point is <m>|k|</m> times the distance from center to object point</li>
                            <li>The image point lies on the opposite side of the center along the same line</li>
                            <li>All corresponding sides are proportional: <m>\frac{OA'}{OA} = \frac{OB'}{OB} = \frac{OC'}{OC} = k</m></li>
                            <li>The shapes remain similar but with opposite orientation</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>Negative enlargements are useful in real-world applications such as reflections in optics, creating mirror images, and understanding symmetry transformations in geometry.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Negative scale factor</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_gx5hn80e">
                In the provided diagram, rectangle <m>ABCD</m> has been enlarged to form rectangle <m>A'B'C'D'</m>, with point <m>O</m> as the center of the enlargement.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="rectangle">
                <caption></caption>
            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="rectangle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Axes
                        \draw[-&gt;] (-4,0) -- (7,0) node[right] {\footnotesize $x$};
                        \draw[-&gt;] (0,-3) -- (0,5) node[above] {\footnotesize $y$};

                        % Origin
                        \node[circle,draw,inner sep=1pt] (O) at (0,0) {};

                        % Large rectangle (ABCD) - Orange with fill
                        \coordinate (A) at (1,1);
                        \coordinate (B) at (1,4);
                        \coordinate (C) at (6,4);
                        \coordinate (D) at (6,1);
                        
                        \filldraw[thick, orange, fill=orange!30] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                        
                        % Small rectangle (A'B'C'D') - Yellow with fill
                        \coordinate (A') at (-1,-1);
                        \coordinate (B') at (-1,-2);
                        \coordinate (C') at (-3,-2);
                        \coordinate (D') at (-3,-1);
                        
                        \filldraw[thick, yellow, fill=yellow!30] (A') -- (B') -- (C') -- (D') -- cycle;

                        % Projection lines from the origin with different colors
                        \draw[dashed, red] (O) -- (A);
                        \draw[dashed, blue] (O) -- (B);
                        \draw[dashed, green] (O) -- (C);
                        \draw[dashed, purple] (O) -- (D);
                        
                        \draw[dashed, red!80!black] (O) -- (A');
                        \draw[dashed, blue!80!black] (O) -- (B');
                        \draw[dashed, green!80!black] (O) -- (C');
                        \draw[dashed, purple!80!black] (O) -- (D');

                        % Points Labels
                        \node[above right] at (A) {\footnotesize A};
                        \node[above left] at (B) {\footnotesize B};
                        \node[above right] at (C) {\footnotesize C};
                        \node[below right] at (D) {\footnotesize D};
                        
                        \node[below right] at (A') {\footnotesize A'};
                        \node[below left] at (B') {\footnotesize B'};
                        \node[below left] at (C') {\footnotesize C'};
                        \node[below right] at (D') {\footnotesize D'};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    </paragraphs>
    <note>
        <p xml:id="auto_prx4ew64">
            If an enlargement has a negative scale factor, the image is formed on the opposite side of the center and is inverted (Upside down).
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_o0tx4biy">
            The rectangle <m>ABCD</m> has been enlarged by a scale factor of <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>
        </p>
    </note>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply negative scale factor enlargement to solve problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Guide learners through worked examples. Emphasize drawing lines through the centre to the opposite side.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Answer Key</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Problem 1:</alert> Enlarge <m>\triangle ABC</m> by scale factor <m>-1</m> about the origin. Draw lines through <m>O</m> to the opposite side. <m>OA = OA' = 5</m> units on the opposite side.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Problem 2:</alert> A circle has radius <m>22.4</m> cm and is enlarged by scale factor <m>0.25</m>. New radius <m>= 22.4 \times 0.25 = 5.6</m> cm. Circumference <m>= 2 \times \frac{22}{7} \times 5.6 = 35.2</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Problem 3:</alert> <m>\triangle ABC</m>: <m>A(-2,9)</m>, <m>B(8,7)</m>, <m>C(5,4)</m>. Scale factor <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> about the origin. <m>A'\left(-1, \frac{9}{2}\right)</m>, <m>B'\left(4, \frac{7}{2}\right)</m>, <m>C'\left(\frac{5}{2}, 2\right)</m>.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Example 1: Scale factor -2 -->
    <example xml:id="example-neg-enlarge-scale-2">
        <!-- <title>Negative Enlargement with Scale Factor <m>-2</m></title> -->
        <statement>
            <p>Triangle <m>PQR</m> has vertices at <m>P(4, 2)</m>, <m>Q(2, 4)</m>, and <m>R(6, 4)</m>. Find the vertices of the image triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m> after a negative enlargement with center at the origin <m>O(0, 0)</m> and scale factor <m>-2</m>.</p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>For a negative enlargement with center at the origin and scale factor <m>k = -2</m>, the image of a point <m>(x, y)</m> is <m>(kx, ky) = (-2x, -2y)</m>.</p>

            <p>Applying this transformation to each vertex:</p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>P(4, 2) \longrightarrow P'(-2 \times 4, -2 \times 2) &amp;= P'(-8, -4)</mrow>
                    <mrow>Q(2, 4) \longrightarrow Q'(-2 \times 2, -2 \times 4) &amp;= Q'(-4, -8)</mrow>
                    <mrow>R(6, 4) \longrightarrow R'(-2 \times 6, -2 \times 4) &amp;= R'(-12, -8)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>The image triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m> has vertices at <m>P'(-8, -4)</m>, <m>Q'(-4, -8)</m>, and <m>R'(-12, -8)</m>.</p>

            <p><alert>Note:</alert> The negative scale factor causes the image to appear on the opposite side of the center of enlargement. Triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m> is twice the size of triangle <m>PQR</m> (since <m>|k| = 2</m>) and is rotated <m>180°</m> about the origin.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- Example 2: Scale factor -1/2 -->
    <example xml:id="example-neg-enlarge-scale-half">
        <!-- <title>Negative Enlargement with Scale Factor <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m></title> -->
        <statement>
            <p>Given rectangle <m>ABCD</m> with vertices at <m>A(3, 2)</m>, <m>B(6, 2)</m>, <m>C(6, 4)</m>, and <m>D(3, 4)</m>, find the image <m>A'B'C'D'</m> after a negative enlargement with center at point <m>O(0, 0)</m> and scale factor <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>For a negative enlargement with scale factor <m>k = -\frac{1}{2}</m>, the image of a point <m>(x, y)</m> is <m>\left(-\frac{1}{2}x, -\frac{1}{2}y\right)</m>.</p>

            <p>Applying this transformation to each vertex:</p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>A(3, 2) \longrightarrow A'\left(-\frac{1}{2} \times 3, -\frac{1}{2} \times 2\right) &amp;= A'\left(-\frac{3}{2}, -1\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>B(6, 2) \longrightarrow B'\left(-\frac{1}{2} \times 6, -\frac{1}{2} \times 2\right) &amp;= B'(-3, -1)</mrow>
                    <mrow>C(6, 4) \longrightarrow C'\left(-\frac{1}{2} \times 6, -\frac{1}{2} \times 4\right) &amp;= C'(-3, -2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>D(3, 4) \longrightarrow D'\left(-\frac{1}{2} \times 3, -\frac{1}{2} \times 4\right) &amp;= D'\left(-\frac{3}{2}, -2\right)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>The image rectangle <m>A'B'C'D'</m> has vertices at <m>A'\left(-\frac{3}{2}, -1\right)</m>, <m>B'(-3, -1)</m>, <m>C'(-3, -2)</m>, and <m>D'\left(-\frac{3}{2}, -2\right)</m>.</p>

            <p><alert>Note:</alert> The scale factor of <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m> means:
                <ul>
                    <li>The image is half the size of the original (linear scale factor magnitude = <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>)</li>
                    <li>The image is positioned on the opposite side of the center (negative sign)</li>
                    <li>The rectangle is rotated <m>180°</m> about the origin</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <!-- Example 3: Multiple scale factors -->
    <example xml:id="example-neg-enlarge-compare">
        <!-- <title>Comparing Different Negative Scale Factors</title> -->
        <statement>
            <p>Given that triangle <m>ABC</m> has vertices <m>A(4, 6)</m>, <m>B(6, 2)</m>, and <m>C(2, 2)</m>, find the vertices of its image after a negative enlargement with origin as the center and the following scale factors:</p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li><m>k = -2</m></li>
                    <li><m>k = -\frac{1}{3}</m></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p>Given the center of enlargement is <m>O(0,0)</m> and scale factor <m>k</m>, we find the coordinates of the image using <m>(x',y') = (kx, ky)</m>.</p>

            <p><m>\textbf{(a) For a scale factor of } k = -2:</m></p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>A(4, 6) \longrightarrow A' &amp;= (-2 \times 4, -2 \times 6) = (-8, -12)</mrow>
                    <mrow>B(6, 2) \longrightarrow B' &amp;= (-2 \times 6, -2 \times 2) = (-12, -4)</mrow>
                    <mrow>C(2, 2) \longrightarrow C' &amp;= (-2 \times 2, -2 \times 2) = (-4, -4)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p><alert>Observations:</alert> The scale factor of <m>-2</m> means the image triangle is:
                <ul>
                    <li>Twice as large as the original (linear scale factor magnitude = <m>2</m>)</li>
                    <li>Positioned on the opposite side of the center (negative sign)</li>
                    <li>Rotated <m>180°</m> about the origin</li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p><m>\textbf{(b) For a scale factor of } k = -\frac{1}{3}:</m></p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>A(4, 6) \longrightarrow A' &amp;= \left(-\frac{1}{3} \times 4, -\frac{1}{3} \times 6\right) = \left(-\frac{4}{3}, -2\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>B(6, 2) \longrightarrow B' &amp;= \left(-\frac{1}{3} \times 6, -\frac{1}{3} \times 2\right) = \left(-2, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>C(2, 2) \longrightarrow C' &amp;= \left(-\frac{1}{3} \times 2, -\frac{1}{3} \times 2\right) = \left(-\frac{2}{3}, -\frac{2}{3}\right)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p><alert>Observations:</alert> The scale factor of <m>-\frac{1}{3}</m> means the image triangle is:
                <ul>
                    <li>One-third the size of the original (linear scale factor magnitude = <m>\frac{1}{3}</m>)</li>
                    <li>Positioned on the opposite side of the center (negative sign)</li>
                    <li>Rotated <m>180°</m> about the origin</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_p3796q48">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ys1eofyp">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ymjkgt6d">
                    Enlarge the triangle <m>ABC</m> by scale factor of <m>-1</m> about the point <m>O</m>.
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="object-enlarge">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image source="object-enl.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_mqxwjpq2">
                    The centre of enlargement is <m>O</m>, the origin. 
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_xgwui35x">
                    Draw a line from point <m>A</m> through <m>O</m> and extend the line upwards through the centre of enlargement.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_gh3girp0">
                    Measure the distance from point <m>O</m> to point <m>A</m>.
                     Since the scale factor is <m>-1</m>, and the distance from <m>OA=5</m>, then <m>OA'=-1\times 5=-5</m> 
                </p>
                <image source="step1.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>

                <p xml:id="auto_e8jjr2hj">
                   Similarly draw the lines from point <m>B</m> through <m>O</m> and <m>C</m> through <m>O</m> and extend the line upwards through the centre of enlargement.
                   Measure the distance from point <m>O</m> to point <m>B'</m> and  <m>O</m> to point <m>C'</m> and multipy by the scale factor <m>-1</m> to get the new distance from  <m>O</m> to point <m>B</m> and  <m>O</m> to point <m>C</m>
                </p>
                <image source="step2.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>

                <p xml:id="auto_5r4x42p1">
                    Join up the points to make the new triangle <m>A'B'C'</m>
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="step">
                    <caption></caption>
                    <image source="step3.png">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Evaluate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Answer Key</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Q1.</alert> <m>X(4,0)</m>, <m>Y(6,3)</m>, <m>Z(5,4)</m>. Centre <m>(1,1)</m>.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Scale factor <m>-2</m>: <m>X'=(-5,3)</m>, <m>Y'=(-9,-3)</m>, <m>Z'=(-7,-5)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Scale factor <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>: <m>X'=(2.5, 0.5)</m>, <m>Y'=(3.5, 2)</m>, <m>Z'=(3, 2.5)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q2.</alert> <m>A(2,6)</m>, <m>B(4,6)</m>, <m>C(4,2)</m>. Centre <m>(0,2)</m>, scale factor <m>-1</m>. <m>A'=(-2,-2)</m>, <m>B'=(-4,-2)</m>, <m>C'=(-4,2)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q3.</alert> <m>P(1,4)</m>, <m>Q(3,4)</m>, <m>R(3,1)</m>. Origin centre.
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Scale factor <m>-\frac{1}{4}</m>: <m>P'\left(-\frac{1}{4}, -1\right)</m>, <m>Q'\left(-\frac{3}{4}, -1\right)</m>, <m>R'\left(-\frac{3}{4}, -\frac{1}{4}\right)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Scale factor <m>-3</m>: <m>P'=(-3,-12)</m>, <m>Q'=(-9,-12)</m>, <m>R'=(-9,-3)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Scale factor <m>2</m>: <m>P'=(2,8)</m>, <m>Q'=(6,8)</m>, <m>R'=(6,2)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q4.</alert> Rectangle <m>5 \times 9</m>. Scale factor <m>-2</m>. Image: <m>10 \times 18</m>, inverted.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q5.</alert> Photo width <m>10 \to 25</m>. Height <m>15 \to 37.5</m> cm.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q6.</alert> Map <m>1:50{,}000</m>. <m>8</m> cm <m>\to 4</m> km.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <!-- Practice Exercises -->
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-negative-enlargements">

        <exercise xml:id="ex-neg-enlarge-1">
            <statement>
                <p>A triangle with vertices <m>X(4, 0)</m>, <m>Y(6, 3)</m>, and <m>Z(5, 4)</m> is enlarged. If the centre of enlargement is <m>(1, 1)</m>, find the coordinates of the image of the triangle when the scale factor is <m>-2</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    The coordinates of the image triangle are <m>X'(-6, -2)</m>, <m>Y'(-10, 4)</m>, and <m>Z'(-8, 6)</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-neg-enlarge-2">
            <statement>
                <p>Points <m>A(2, 6)</m>, <m>B(4, 6)</m>, and <m>C(4, 2)</m> are the vertices of a triangle. Taking point <m>(0, 2)</m> as the centre of enlargement, find the coordinates of its image when the scale factor is <m>-1</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    The coordinates of the image triangle are <m>A'(-2, -2)</m>, <m>B'(0, -2)</m>, and <m>C'(0, 2)</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-neg-enlarge-3">
            <statement>
                <p>Points <m>P(1, 4)</m>, <m>Q(3, 4)</m>, and <m>R(3, 1)</m> are vertices of a triangle. Taking the origin as the centre of enlargement, find the image when the scale factor is:</p>
                <ol>
                    <li><m>-\frac{1}{4}</m></li>
                    <li><m>-3</m></li>
                </ol>
            </statement>
                <answer>
                    <p>
                        (a) The coordinates of the image triangle are <m>P'\left(-\frac{1}{4}, -1\right)</m>, <m>Q'\left(-\frac{3}{4}, -1\right)</m>, and <m>R'\left(-\frac{3}{4}, -\frac{1}{4}\right)</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        (b) The coordinates of the image triangle are <m>P'(-3, -12)</m>, <m>Q'(-9, -12)</m>, and <m>R'(-9, -3)</m>.
                    </p>
                </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-neg-enlarge-4">
            <statement>
                   <p>
                     A square measures <m>5 \text{ cm}</m> by <m>5 \text{ cm}</m>. 
                     Find the corresponding measurements of the image of the square after an enlargement with scale factor <m>-2</m>.
                   </p>
            </statement>
                <answer>
                       <p>
                          The image of the square will have sides measuring <m>10 \text{ cm}</m> by <m>10 \text{ cm}</m>.
                      </p>
                </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-neg-enlarge-5">
            <statement>
                <p>Triangle <m>ABC</m> has sides <m>AB = 6 \text{ cm}</m>, <m>BC = 8 \text{ cm}</m>, and <m>AC = 10 \text{ cm}</m>. Find the sides of the image triangle after a negative enlargement with scale factor <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
                <answer>
                      <p>
                         The sides of the image triangle will be <m>3 \text{ cm}</m>, <m>4 \text{ cm}</m>, and <m>5 \text{ cm}</m>.
                      </p>
                </answer>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn grids with colour coding (blue from object to centre, red from centre to image). Start with scale factor <m>-1</m> only. Use a step-by-step checklist: (1) Plot original, (2) Draw rays through centre to opposite side, (3) Measure distances, (4) Plot image points on opposite side.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>Complete all problems using both construction and coordinate methods. Encourage peer explanation of method.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Successive enlargements: prove that the composition of two enlargements with scale factors <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m> gives a combined scale factor of <m>k_1 \times k_2</m>. Area scales by <m>k^2</m>.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activities</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\triangle PQR</m>: <m>P(1,1)</m>, <m>Q(3,1)</m>, <m>R(2,3)</m>.
                        <ol marker="(a)">
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Scale factor <m>-2</m> about origin: <m>P'=(-2,-2)</m>, <m>Q'=(-6,-2)</m>, <m>R'=(-4,-6)</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Scale factor <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m> of the image: <m>P''=(1,1)</m>, <m>Q''=(3,1)</m>, <m>R''=(2,3)</m>.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Combined scale factor <m>= (-2) \times \left(-\frac{1}{2}\right) = 1</m>, which returns to the original triangle.
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Area <m>= 6</m> cm<m>^2</m>, scale factor <m>-3</m>. Area scale factor <m>= (-3)^2 = 9</m>. New area <m>= 6 \times 9 = 54</m> cm<m>^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        A building is <m>12</m> m tall with a shadow of <m>8</m> m. A model has scale factor <m>-\frac{1}{100}</m>. Model height <m>= 12</m> cm, shadow <m>= 8</m> cm, inverted.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
</subsubsection>